<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Ttide | Gunnar Voet</title><link>https://gunnarvoet.net/tags/ttide/</link><atom:link href="https://gunnarvoet.net/tags/ttide/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><description>Ttide</description><generator>Source Themes Academic (https://sourcethemes.com/academic/)</generator><language>en-us</language><copyright>© 2025 Gunnar Voet</copyright><lastBuildDate>Tue, 10 Mar 2015 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><image><url>https://gunnarvoet.net/images/icon_hu2368079832697477974.png</url><title>Ttide</title><link>https://gunnarvoet.net/tags/ttide/</link></image><item><title>Research Cruises Tasman Sea 2015</title><link>https://gunnarvoet.net/post/research-cruise-ttide-2015/</link><pubDate>Tue, 10 Mar 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://gunnarvoet.net/post/research-cruise-ttide-2015/</guid><description>&lt;p>In January and March 2015 I went on two research cruises on R/V Roger Revelle to the Tasman Sea. I oversaw technical details, logistics, deployments and recoveries of the 15 TTIDE moorings, some of them full ocean depth down to 4000 m. The TTIDE project aimed at understanding the dissipation and reflection of internal tides impinging on a continental shelf. Working close to the Southern Ocean turned out to be quite challenging with strong winds and high seas for most of the time.&lt;/p>
